        const contentData = {
            title: "Electric charges and Field",
            sections: [{
                id: "electrostatic",
                heading: "Electrostatic",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>The branch of physics in which we deal with force, electric field, potential when charge is at rest.</p>
                    <div class="math-block">\\[\\frac{dQ_{\\mathrm{r}}}{dt} = 0\\]</div>
                    <p>Where \\(Q_{\\mathrm{r}}\\) is the position of charge particle. This means the position of charge is not changing with time.</p>
                    <div class="math-block">\\[\\frac{dQ}{dt} = 0\\]</div>
                    <p>This means the charge is constant the value of charge is not changing with time.</p>
                `
            }, {
                id: "charge",
                heading: "Charge",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>It is fundamental properties of a body which obtained by gaining or loosing of electrons. If a body loose electron it gets positive charge and if a body gains electron it get negative charge. It is denoted by \\(Q\\) . Its SI unit is coulomb.</p>
                `
            }, {
                id: "ancient-observations",
                heading: "Ancient Observations (600 BCE - 1600 CE)",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>Thales of Miletus (600 BCE): Noticed that rubbing amber (Greek: elektron) with fur attracted lightweight objects (static electricity).</p>
                    <p>Benjamin Franklin (1750s): gives the name positive and negative.</p>
                    <p>Some pairs of objects which get charge by rubbing.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Plastic rod with wool cloth or cat fur  - Plastic rod gets negative charge while wool or cat fur get positive charge.</li>
                        <li>Glass rod with silk  - Glass rod gets positive charge while silk cloth negative charge.</li>
                        <li>Glass rod with wool  - Glass rod gets negative charge while wool cloth gets positive charge.</li>
                    </ol>
                `
            }, {
                id: "polarity-of-charge",
                heading: "Polarity of charge",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>The property of charge which differentiates the types of charge is known as the polarity of charge.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Like charge repel each other while unlike charge attract each other. <br />Two positive or two negative charges repel each other while one positive and another negative charge attract each other.</li>
                        <li>Additive of charge <br />Charge is scaler quantity hence charge is just added algebraically.</li>
                        <li>Charge is conserved <br />The total charge of an isolated system is always conserve, charge is neither created or destroy.</li>
                        <li>Quantisation of charge <br />"Quantisation of charge means that charge exists in discrete amounts and is always an integral multiple of the elementary charge." <br />The basic relation is: <div class="math-block">\\[q=ne\\]</div> where: <br />\\(q =\\) charge on the object <br />\\(n =\\) integer <br />\\(e =\\) elementary charge \\((1.6\\times10^{- 19}\\,\\text{C})\\) <br /><br />Why the charge on any object is integral multiple of e? <br />A body gets charged by losing or gaining electrons. Since electrons are indestructible, the transfer of electrons occurs in integral numbers. Therefore, the charge on a body is always an integral multiple of \\(e\\) .</li>
                    </ol>
                `
            }, {
                id: "gold-leaf-electroscope",
                heading: "Gold leaf electroscope",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>It is a device which used to measure the amount of charge. This work on the principal that like charge repel each other.</p>
                `
            }, {
                id: "coulombs-law",
                heading: "Coulomb's law",
                level: 1,
                content: `
                    <p>We have seen that two charges apply force on each other so coulombs law is about the magnitude of force. The forces between two charges is knowns as columbic force or electrostatic force. Coulombs law states that the coulombic force between two charges is directly proportional to the product of magnitude of both charges and inversely proportional to the square of distance between them.</p>
                    <div class="diagram">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 400 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                            <circle cx="100" cy="100" r="30" fill="#2563eb" />
                            <text x="85" y="108" fill="white" font-weight="bold" font-size="18">q₁</text>
                            <circle cx="300" cy="100" r="30" fill="#ef4444" />
                            <text x="285" y="108" fill="white" font-weight="bold" font-size="18">q₂</text>
                            <line x1="130" y1="100" x2="270" y2="100" stroke="#0f172a" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4" />
                            <text x="180" y="90" font-size="16" fill="#475569">r</text>
                            <path d="M140 80 L160 80 L150 70 Z" fill="#2563eb" />
                            <path d="M260 120 L240 120 L250 130 Z" fill="#ef4444" />
                            <text x="130" y="70" font-size="14" fill="#2563eb">F</text>
                            <text x="270" y="140" font-size="14" fill="#ef4444">F</text>
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    <div class="math-block">
                        \\[F\\propto q_1q_2 \\quad (i)\\]
                        \\[F\\propto \\frac{1}{r^2} \\quad (ii)\\]
                    </div>
                    <p>On adding equation (i) and (ii)</p>
                    <div class="math-block">\\[F = \\frac{kq_1q_2}{r^2}\\]</div>
                    <p>Were, <br />F = electrostatic force <br />\\(q_{1},q_{2} =\\) charges <br />\\(r =\\) distance between charges <br />\\(k =\\) Coulomb constant whose value is \\(9\\times10^{9}\\,\\text{Nm}^{2}/\\text{C}^{2}\\) <br />\\(\\epsilon_0\\) is the permittivity of free space</p>
                    <div class="math-block">\\[k = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\epsilon_0}\\]</div>
                    <p>Were, <br />\\(\\epsilon_0 = 8.854\\times10^{-12}\\,\\text{C}^2/\\text{Nm}^2\\)</p>
                    <h4>Vector form of coulomb law</h4>
                    <div class="diagram">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 400 250" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                            <circle cx="100" cy="150" r="20" fill="#2563eb" />
                            <text x="90" y="156" fill="white" font-weight="bold" font-size="14">q₁</text>
                            <circle cx="300" cy="100" r="20" fill="#ef4444" />
                            <text x="290" y="106" fill="white" font-weight="bold" font-size="14">q₂</text>
                            <line x1="120" y1="150" x2="280" y2="100" stroke="#0f172a" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4" />
                            <text x="185" y="115" font-size="14" fill="#475569">r</text>
                            <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="100" y2="150" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="2" />
                            <text x="60" y="210" font-size="14" fill="#2563eb">r₁</text>
                            <line x1="50" y1="200" x2="300" y2="100" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="2" />
                            <text x="240" y="100" font-size="14" fill="#ef4444">r₂</text>
                            <path d="M110 155 L250 110 L240 100 L260 105 Z" fill="#2563eb" />
                            <text x="160" y="130" font-size="14" fill="#2563eb">r₂₁</text>
                        </svg>
                    </div>
                    <p>Applying triangle law of vector addition</p>
                    <div class="math-block">
                        \\[\\mathbf{r}_2 = \\mathbf{r}_1 + \\mathbf{r}_{21}\\]
                        \\[\\mathbf{r}_{21} = \\mathbf{r}_2 - \\mathbf{r}_1\\]
                        \\[\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}_{21} = \\frac{\\mathbf{r}_2 - \\mathbf{r}_1}{|\\mathbf{r}_2 - \\mathbf{r}_1|}\\]
                    </div>
                    <p>\\(\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}_{21}\\) is the unit vector in the direction of \\(\\mathbf{r}_{21}\\) .</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Unit vector is a vector which denotes the direction of a vector and whose magnitude is 1.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="math-block">\\[\\vec{F}_{21} = \\frac{kq_1q_2}{r^2}\\hat{r}_{21}\\]</div>
                    <div class="diagram">
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 400 250" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                            <circle cx="300" cy="100" r="20" fill="#2563eb" />
